–Overleden","1300–Male":"1300–Overleden","1215–Male":"1215–Overleden","1225–Female":"1225–Overleden","about 1290":"circa 1290","1296":"1296","1252":"1252","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","abt. 1250":"circa 1250","1270":"1270","abt. 1295":"circa 1295","1215":"1215","1369":"1369","1225":"1225","1323":"1323","ABT 1298":"circa 1298","1300":"1300","ABT 1300":"circa 1300","1298":"1298","1318":"1318","1306":"1306","Skaraborg, Dalarnas, Sweden":"Zweden","Vinstorpa, Skaraborg, Sweden":"Skaraborg, Zweden"},"en":{"abt. 1250–":"about 1250–Deceased","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1252–Male":"1252–Deceased","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1295–Male":"1295–Deceased","1296–1369":"1296–1369","1298–Male":"1298–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1215–Male":"1215–Deceased","1225–Female":"1225–Deceased","about 1290":"about 1290","1296":"1296","1252":"1252","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","abt. 1250":"about 1250","1270":"1270","abt. 1295":"about 1295","1215":"1215","1369":"1369","1225":"1225","1323":"1323","ABT 1298":"about 1298","1300":"1300","ABT 1300":"about 1300","1298":"1298","1318":"1318","1306":"1306","Skaraborg, Dalarnas, Sweden":"Sweden","Vinstorpa, Skaraborg, Sweden":"Skaraborg, Sweden","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mattsson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Anders, Erik, Matts, Nils, Bjorn, Gunvor, Per, Sten, Thor, Thorvald, Torvald.","Swedish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Matts</i>, a short form of <i>Matthias</i> or <i>Mattheus</i> (see   Matthew  ). Compare   Matson   and   Mattson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mattson","meanings":["Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish   Mattsson  .","Americanized form of Danish and Norwegian   Mattsen   and   Madsen  , cognates of 1.","English (mainly Yorkshire and Derbyshire): variant of   Matson  ."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]}]},{"name":"Hakan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from the Old Norse personal name <i>Hákon</i>, from <i>hā</i> ‘horse’ or ‘high’ + <i>konr</i> ‘son, descendant’; borne by  Haakon VII  of Norway (  1872–1957 ), and by  Crown Prince Haakon Magnus  (  b. 1973 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hagen","meanings":["1  Germanic: short form of various compound names formed with <i>hag</i> ‘stockade, enclosure’.","2  Altered form of Nordic <b>Håkon</b> ."]},{"name":"Hakon","meanings":["from the Old Norse personal name <i>Hákon</i>, from <i>hā</i> ‘horse’ or ‘high’ + <i>konr</i> ‘son, descendant’; borne by  Haakon VII  of Norway (  1872–1957 ), and by  Crown Prince Haakon Magnus  (  b. 1973 )."]},{"name":"Håkan","meanings":["from the Old Norse personal name <i>Hákon</i>, from <i>hā</i> ‘horse’ or ‘high’ + <i>konr</i> ‘son, descendant’; borne by  Haakon VII  of Norway (  1872–1957 ), and by  Crown Prince Haakon Magnus  (  b. 1973 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1357046,"age":0,"year":"1250","julianDay":2177614,"description":"King Eriksson died. Valdemar crowned King. Birger Jarl declared regent until Valdemar is of age.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1702074,"age":2,"year":"1252","julianDay":2178344,"title":"Earliest Mention of Stockholm","description":"The earliest known recorded history of the city of Stockholm is in Norse sagas as Agnafit which dates to 1252. The city rose to prominence due to Baltic trade. Stockholm is now the most populous urban area in the region.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1702075,"age":56,"year":"1306","julianDay":2198067,"title":"The Hatuna Games","description":"A conflict on September 29, 1306, between Birger, King of Sweden, and his brothers, the dukes Eric Magnusson and Valdemar Magnusson is known as The Hatuna Games. The brothers arrived to a party late in the night at King Birger's estate. The dukes captured and imprisoned Birger and his wife in Nykoping Castle's dungeon. Duke Eric then gained power over Sweden.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1357048,"age":68,"year":"1318","julianDay":2202450,"description":"Peasants revolted against King.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1357049,"age":73,"year":"1323","julianDay":2204276,"description":"Sweden and Russia establish border.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1357050,"age":100,"year":"1350","julianDay":2214138,"description":"Black Death killed one-third of population.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Hakan Mattsson was born about 1250, in Skaraborg, Sweden, his father, Matts Anbjornsson, was 37 and his mother, Mrs. Matts Ambjornsson, was 27. He married Mrs- Hakan